I89. Responsibilities and relief from liability of certifying officials

I11(a) A certifying official certifying a voucher is responsible for_

I12(1) information stated in the certificate, voucher, and supporting records;

I12(2) the computation of a certified voucher under this section and section 3325 of this title;

I12(3) the legality of a proposed payment under the appropriation or fund involved;

I12(4) repaying a payment_

I13(A) illegal, improper, or incorrect because of an inaccurate or misleading certificate;

I13(B) prohibited by law; or

I13(C) that does not represent a legal obligation under the appropriation or fund involved; and

Q04

I12(5) verifying transportation rates, freight classifications, and other information provided on a Government bill of lading or transportation request, unless the Administrator of General Services has determined that verification by a prepayment audit conducted pursuant to section 3726(a) of this title for a particular mode or modes of transportation, or for an agency or subagency, will not adequately protect the interests of the Government.

Q04

I11(b)(1) The Comptroller General may relieve a certifying official from liability when the Comptroller General decides that_

I12(A) the certification was based on official records and the official did not know, and by reasonable diligence and inquiry could not have discovered, the correct information; or

I12(B)(i) the obligation was incurred in good faith;

I12(ii) no law specifically prohibited the payment; and

I12(iii) the United States Government received value for payment.

Q04

I11(2) The Comptroller General may deny relief when the Comptroller General decides the head of the agency did not carry out diligently collection action under procedures prescribed by the Comptroller General.

I11(c) The Comptroller General shall relieve a certifying official from liability for an overpayment_

I12(1) to a common carrier under section 3726 of this title when the Comptroller General decides the overpayment occurred only because the administrative audit before payment did not verify transportation rates, freight classifications, or land-grant deductions and the Administrator of General Services has determined that verification by a prepayment audit conducted pursuant to section 3726(a) of this title for a particular mode or modes of transportation, or for an agency or subagency, will not adequately protect the interests of the Government; or

