I12(2) T4Purpose and objectiveK._It is the purpose of this section to provide a mechanism for designating any area where money laundering or a related financial crime appears to be occurring at a higher than average rate such that_

I13(A) a comprehensive approach to the problem of such crime in such area can be developed, in cooperation with State and local law enforcement agencies, which utilizes the authority of the Secretary to prevent such activity; or

I13(B) such area can be targeted for law enforcement action.

Q04

I11(b) T4Element of National StrategyK._The designation of certain areas as areas in which money laundering and related financial crimes are extensive or present a substantial risk shall be an element of the national strategy developed pursuant to section 5341(b).

I11(c) T4Designation of Areas._

I12(1) T4Designation by secretaryK._The Secretary, after taking into consideration the factors specified in subsection (d), shall designate any geographical area, industry, sector, or institution in the United States in which money laundering and related financial crimes are extensive or present a substantial risk as a ``high-risk money laundering and related financial crimes area''.

I12(2) T4Case-by-case determination in consultation with the attorney generalK._In addition to the factors specified in subsection (d), any designation of any area under paragraph (1) shall be made on the basis of a determination by the Secretary, in consultation with the Attorney General, that the particular area, industry, sector, or institution is being victimized by, or is particularly vulnerable to, money laundering and related financial crimes.

I12(3) T4Specific initiativesK._Any head of a department, bureau, or law enforcement agency, including any State or local prosecutor, involved in the detection, prevention, and suppression of money laundering and related financial crimes and any State or local official or prosecutor may submit_

I13(A) a written request for the designation of any area as a high-risk money laundering and related financial crimes area; or

I13(B) a written request for funding under section 5351 for a specific prevention or enforcement initiative, or to determine the extent of financial criminal activity, in an area.

Q04

I11(d) T4FactorsK._In considering the designation of any area as a high-risk money laundering and related financial crimes area, the Secretary shall, to the extent appropriate and in consultation with the Attorney General, take into account the following factors:

I12(1) The population of the area.

I12(2) The number of bank and nonbank financial institution transactions which originate in such area or involve institutions located in such area.

I12(3) The number of stock or commodities transactions which originate in such area or involve institutions located in such area.

I12(4) Whether the area is a key transportation hub with any international ports or airports or an extensive highway system.

I12(5) Whether the area is an international center for banking or commerce.

I12(6) The extent to which financial crimes and financial crime-related activities in such area are having a harmful impact in other areas of the country.

I12(7) The number or nature of requests for information or analytical assistance which_

I13(A) are made to the analytical component of the Department of the Treasury; and

I13(B) originate from law enforcement or regulatory authorities located in such area or involve institutions or businesses located in such area or residents of such area.

Q04

I12(8) The volume or nature of suspicious activity reports originating in the area.

I12(9) The volume or nature of currency transaction reports or reports of cross-border movements of currency or monetary instruments originating in, or transported through, the area.

I12(10) Whether, and how often, the area has been the subject of a geographical targeting order.

I12(11) Observed changes in trends and patterns of money laundering activity.

I12(12) Unusual patterns, anomalies, growth, or other changes in the volume or nature of core economic statistics or indicators.

I12(13) Statistics or indicators of unusual or unexplained volumes of cash transactions.

I12(14) Unusual patterns, anomalies, or changes in the volume or nature of transactions conducted through financial institutions operating within or outside the United States.

